SIMPLE: engender
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Engender
<hw>En*gen"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Engendered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Engendering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>engender</ets>, L. <ets>ingenerare</ets>; <ets>in + generare</ets>
to beget. See <er>Generate</er>, and cf. <er>Ingenerate</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To produce by the union of the sexes; to beget.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to exist; to bring forth; to produce; to
sow the seeds of; <as>as, angry words <ex>engender</ex>
strife</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Engendering</qex> friendship in all parts of the common
wealth.</q> <rj><qau>Southey.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To breed; generate; procreate; propagate;
occasion; call forth; cause; excite; develop.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Engender</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Engender
<hw>En*gen"der</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To assume form;
to come into existence; to be caused or produced.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thick clouds are spread, and storms <qex>engender</qex> there.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To come together; to meet, as in sexual
embrace.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧I saw their mouths <xex>engender</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Massinger.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Engender</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Engender
<hw>En*gen"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that
which, engenders.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Engendrure</ent>⟦br⟧
